dataIdInfo.idAbs: Annual Five-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for 2015 to 2030 for the national, and first- and second-order administrative division levels of Papua New Guinea were prepared by the U.S. Census Bureau for joining (linking) to shapefiles as attribute data. The estimates are consistent with the midyear national projections from the U.S. Census Bureau International Data Base (IDB).
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The U.S. Census Bureau is providing annual subnational five-year age group population estimates by sex for Papua New Guinea for 2015-2030 in a geographic information system (GIS) for users of the Spatial Data Repository, funded by the U.S. Presidentâ€™s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR).

CENSUS DATA 2011 Age-Sex Data: Papua New Guinea National Population and Housing Census 2011, LLG Population Data by 5 Year Age Group. National Statistics Office of Papua New Guinea. Not available online, received via email directly from National Statistics Office of Papua New Guinea upon request by USCB staff on September 28, 2020.

National Statistics Office of Papua New Guinea. Available online at http://www.nso.gov.pg/download/77/nso-digital-library/2246/png-final-figures-2011-booklet-2.pdf (accessed January 18, 2022).
The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of non-U.S. census and survey data.

dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
SUBNATIONAL DIVISIONS Papua New Guinea's second-order administrative divisions: 87 districts as of the 2011 census.
SHAPEFILES The original shapefile downloaded from the Humanitarian Data Exchange had 326 polygons and matched the 2011 census local level governments (third-order administrative divisions) with no changes to the subnational boundaries made by USCB staff. The U.S. Census Bureau aligned the shapefile's national boundary to the Large Scale International Boundary Line (LSIB) polygon file from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues. Finally, the LSIB-aligned shapefile was dissolved into 87 polygons, one for each of Papua New Guinea's second-order administrative divisions (districts) as reported by the National Statistics Office of Papua New Guinea in the 2011 census.
NOTES (1) The Coale-Demeny empirical model was used by U.S. Census Bureau staff to disaggregate the "75-plus" age group found in the 2011 census data received from the National Statistics Office of Papua New Guinea into the "75-79" and "80-plus" age groups used for these estimates and projections. (2) The 2011 census data received from the National Statistics Office of Papua New Guinea included an "age not stated" field, which was divided and redistributed among the age groups for each sex by Census Bureau staff, according to each age group's percentage of the total population by sex. (3) District, province, and national level data were summed by USCB staff from Local Level Government (LLG) data received from the National Statistics Office of Papua New Guinea.
FEATURE AND ATTRIBUTE DETAILS The 2015-2030 population estimates for Papua New Guinea's administrative divisions are provided in the following two tables: (1) The Unicode tab-delimited text file (table) "Papua New Guinea_5yr_age_sex_2015-2030_uscb_mar2022.txt," which can be joined to the shapefile via the common field "GEO_MATCH." (2) The Excel table "Papua New Guinea_5yr_age_sex_2015-2030_508_uscb_mar2022.xlsx," formatted for accessibility in compliance with Section 508 of the U.S. Government's Federal Rehabilitation Act.
Details on processing of the census data and calculation of 2015-2030 estimates are provided in the "Census Metadata" tab of the Excel file and "Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas" document. For the subnational areas, the U.S. Board on Geographic Names (BGN) "approved" names from the NGA GEOnet Names Server (cited in the "Credits") were used. For any area that a BGN name was not available, the name from the national census was used. Official codes for the subnational areas from the country's national statistical office, when available, are entered in the "NSO_CODE" field in both the text and Excel tables. Information on any alternative area names or recent name or boundary changes is entered in the "USCBCMNT" field. A partial list of the fields in the Excel and Unicode text files, including all fields identifying geographic names and codes, is provided in the Excel file's "Data Dictionary" tab. More detail on the U.S. Census Bureau subnational age and sex group estimates and maps for PEPFAR can be found in the document "Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository." It includes a data dictionary that is similar to that in the Excel table.
METHODOLOGY For more information, see the following methodology documents in the Spatial Data Repository: (1) "U.S. Census Bureau Methodology for SDR Subnational Population Estimates." (2) "U.S. Census Bureau Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas." (3) "Instructions for Joining Subnational Population Data to Shapefiles."
ACCESS The U.S. Census Bureauâ€™s products for PEPFAR can be accessed from the Spatial Data Repository at http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/home/, which also provides access to data and maps from the DHS (Demographic and Health Surveys) Program. A zipped file containing shapefiles with metadata, an Excel workbook with subnational population estimates, and a Unicode tab-delimited text file is available for each country. PEPFAR products are also available on the Census Bureau website at http://www.census.gov/geographies/mapping-files/time-series/demo/international-programs/subnationalpopulation.html for download.
